            "abstractNote": "The diet of the golden‐tipped bat (\n              Kerivoula papuensis\n              ) was investigated by collecting faecal samples from captured individuals in the Richmond Range State Forest, north‐eastern New South Wales, Australia. Faecal analysis was used so that all captured individuals could be released after processing and banding. A total of 53 faecal pellets were collected in the summer and autumn months from 39 individuals. The major food of\n              K. papuensis\n              were spiders (Araneida) comprising 91.9% of the total volume of food. Other foods consumed in small quantities were Coleoptera, Lepidoptera and Diptera.",
